I'm not sure why it's not working in my vanilla instance of visual studio - any thoughts would be appreciated.

The following is not currently compiling when I feel it should. If this was an intentional design decision, then it is one that I personally disagree with, but I am assuming this is a bug.

You cannot call extension methods directly via `using static`:
```cs
using static HelloWorld;

static class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        A(default);
        B(default); // <- not working
    }
}

public static class HelloWorld
{
    public static void A(int a) { }
    public static void B(this int a) { }
}
```
This is forcing me to me to have two copies of methods, one (non-extension version) in a class intended to be used with a `using static` and one (extension version) in another class that is not intended to be used with `using static`.

My Environment:
- Visual Studio 2019 Preview
- Target: netcoreapp3.1
- C# version: latest

